---

<Base
  title="MODUS · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="An exploratory language-model pilot developing methods to separate modal function from modal vocabulary: controlled experiments on modal force, lexical form, evidence, and causal intervention."
  toc={true}
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Exploratory · methods pilot
    </div>
    <h1>MODUS: separating modal function from modal vocabulary</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      An exploratory language-model pilot developing methods for one narrow problem: when a model
      handles <em>must</em> and <em>might</em>, how would you tell whether anything is running on the
      modal <strong>function</strong> rather than on the modal <strong>word</strong>? Controlled
      experiments on modal force, lexical form, evidence, and causal intervention.
    </p>

    <p>
      MODUS is <strong>methods groundwork</strong>, not a finding. It exists because the question I
      actually care about —
      <a href="/research">whether an epistemic possibility expression keeps a content-specific
      alternative available for subsequent reasoning</a> — needs an instrument that can hold the
      information constant and vary only the linguistic form, and needs that instrument to survive
      the obvious confounds before any of its outputs mean anything. This page is that instrument
      being built and stress-tested.
    </p>

    <h2>What the pilot does</h2>
    <p>On the running example "the ball is red":</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Build a certainty direction <code>D</code> with no modal words.</strong> Hold the
        fact fixed and vary only the evidence: "all three sensors report red" (sure) vs. "one of three
        reports red" (unsure). The internal difference gives <code>D</code>, evidence-based certainty,
        with no <em>must</em> / <em>might</em> in it.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the anchors.</strong> "must be red" and "might be red" should land on the sure
        and unsure ends of <code>D</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Intervene.</strong> Remove <code>D</code> from a "might be red" sentence and see
        whether the model's certainty-related behaviour moves.</li>
      <li><strong>Control.</strong> <code>D</code> could be encoding the evidence description itself
        (how many sensors report red) rather than certainty. So compare it against a competing
        <strong>base-rate</strong> direction <code>D′</code>, built by changing how many red balls are
        in the box instead of the evidence. Removing <code>D</code> should move <em>might</em> while
        removing <code>D′</code> should not.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      It builds on two papers. Wagner &amp; Zarrieß (IWCS) is the closest prior work; because it uses
      natural data and a read-only probe, its negative result is hard to read, so the pilot tries to
      close that gap with controlled sentences and by intervening, not just decoding. Cho's continuous
      steering gives the key move: treat the modal signal as a direction one can dial and test
      causally.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Pilot, done — a smoke test.</strong> Qwen2.5-0.5B, one evidence family: the direction
      <code>D</code> is built from evidence alone, with no modal word present; ablating it while the
      model answers a <em>might</em> item raises that item's certainty by <strong>+0.152</strong>,
      while ablating the base-rate control <code>D′</code> does nothing (−0.033).
    </p>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Caveats that keep it a smoke test, and they are not incidental: the ablation
      <em>overshoots</em> (might ends above the must level, so "moves toward must" is loose); the
      must/might baseline gap is small (0.063); and a norm-matched random-direction control is still
      needed to exclude generic disruption. Until that control exists, generic disruption is a live
      explanation of the whole effect. It is one model, one evidence family, one run.
    </p>

    <h2>What this can and cannot support</h2>
    <p>Worth stating flatly, because each of these has a tempting overstatement one step away.</p>
    <p><strong>It can support:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>that a direction can be constructed from evidence contrasts containing no modal words;</li>
      <li>that <em>must</em> and <em>might</em> associate with that direction;</li>
      <li>a preliminary test of whether intervening on it changes certainty-related behaviour;</li>
      <li>that the lexical, base-rate, and generic-disruption confounds are real and testable, and
        what it takes to separate them;</li>
      <li>a methodological basis for the alternative-maintenance experiments this is groundwork for.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>It cannot support:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>that the model implements Kratzer-style worlds — or any claim that internal geometry
        adjudicates between competing semantic theories;</li>
      <li>that the model maintains live alternatives (the pilot does not test maintenance at all);</li>
      <li>that humans and language models share a modal representation;</li>
      <li>that the direction is a stable causal finding — one run, one model, one family, and a
        missing control.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why the geometry does not settle the semantics</h2>
    <p>
      An earlier version of this project was built the other way round: read the internal
      representation, decide whether it is a set of alternatives (Kratzer) or a scalar degree
      (Lassiter), and treat that as evidence about modal semantics. I have retired that framing. A
      linear direction that correlates with certainty is a linear direction that correlates with
      certainty; naming it a world-set is a decision made outside the data. Those two analyses are
      still the competing explanations that make the topic worth working on — but they have to be
      separated by what a modal <em>does</em>, downstream, that a certainty-matched non-modal does
      not. Behaviour first; representation only if the behaviour is there; intervention only to test
      what the representation is carrying.
    </p>
    <p>
      That reordering is what demoted this project from a thesis flagship to what it should always
      have been: a methods pilot that makes the real experiments possible.
    </p>

    <h2>Scope &amp; claim discipline</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Epistemic force only</strong>: <em>must</em> / <em>might</em> as evidence-licensed
        inference (von Fintel &amp; Gillies 2010), not logical necessity.</li>
      <li>ML vocabulary stays <strong>instrument</strong> vocabulary. The model is a system whose
        input is entirely linguistic, which makes it a good probe of what linguistic distribution can
        deliver — never a claim that "the model understands modality".</li>
      <li>No claim about people. Convergence ≠ homology, and a model result is not evidence about a
        mind.</li>
      <li>Primary venues are semantics-side (SALT, <em>Semantics &amp; Pragmatics</em>, Sinn und
        Bedeutung, IWCS); interpretability venues are a secondary, methods-facing outlet.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</Base>
